UA Flights Departure Delay Analysis

Wai Chun (Jun) Chong

28 October 2022

1 Problem Statement

To improve both efficiency and customer satisfaction, I would mainly focus study the temporal and environmental factors causing the flight delay including but not limited to:

  1. Time of day
  2. Time of year
  3. Temperature
  4. Wind speed
  5. Precipitation
  6. Visibility

from data flights and weather.

Due to high value of customer satisfaction, we should not ignore the outlier cases in each factor, but instead we have to take account of those cases and analyze them. Therefore, I would compare the mean and median of each case to find out which numerical summary we should use for analysis and permutation test.

From the box-plot and monthly mean line-plot of departure delays, it seems that mean shows a significant differences in comparison. Besides, Summer (June, July, August) seems to show a great mean difference with After Summer (September, October, November).

2.1 Summer vs After Summer

\(H_{0}: \mu_{s} - \mu_{a} = 0\)
\(H_{a}: \mu_{s} - \mu_{a} > 0\)

In the conclusion, since p-value is 10^{-4} (less than 0.05), it is statistically significant to say that there is a difference of departure delays between Summer and After Summer.

Figure 3.2 The Boxplot and Mean Lineplot of Average Departure Delay over the Day

From the box-plot and hourly mean line-plot of departure delays, it seems that mean shows a significant differences in comparison. Besides, night hours (after 8pm) seems to have a greater significant difference than early morning hours (before 8am).

3.1 Night hours vs Early morning hours

\(H_{0}: \mu_{n} - \mu_{e} = 0\)
\(H_{a}: \mu_{n} - \mu_{e} > 0\)

In the conclusion, since p-value is 10^{-4} (less than 0.05), it is statistically significant to say that there is a difference of departure delays between night hours (after 8pm) and early morning hours (before 8am).

4 Temperature and Departure Delay

Figure 4.1 The Mean and Median Lineplot of Departure Delay over the Temperature

From the line and point plots above, we see that there is a significant difference shown from mean of departure delays. It does not really show a certain range of temperature that indicate will be a great influence to the departure delay, but fluctuating throughout the entire data. To my personal interest, I would like to do a test on extreme temperature vs moderate temperature.

4.1 Extreme Temperature vs Moderate Temperature

Table 4.2 The Mean of Departure Delay with respect to Extreme and Moderate Temperature
Mean(Extreme Temperature) Mean(Moderate Temperature)
13.67428 11.22549

\(H_{0}: \mu_{T} - \mu_{t} = 0\)
\(H_{a}: \mu_{T} - \mu_{t} > 0\)

In the conclusion, since p-value is 10^{-4} (less than 0.05), it is statistically significant to say that there is a difference of departure delays between extreme temperature and moderate temperature.

5 Wind speed and Departure Delay

Figure 5.1 The Mean and Median Lineplot of Departure Delay over the Wind Speed

From both mean and median line-plots above, we can see that both mean and median plots shows a greater significant fluctuation of departure delays as wind speed increases. Therefore, I will do a test on high wind speed vs low wind speed using permutation test on ratio of standard deviation.

5.1 High Wind Speed vs Low Wind Speed

Table 5.2 The SD of Departure Delay with respect to High and Low Wind
SD(High Wind) SD(Low Wind)
36.39903 34.79615

\(H_{0}: \frac{\sigma_{W}}{\sigma_{w}} = 1\)
\(H_{a}: \frac{\sigma_{W}}{\sigma_{w}} > 1\)

In the conclusion, since p-value is 0.3555 (greater than 0.05), it is not statistically significant to say that there is a greater ratio difference of departure delays between high wind speed and low speed wind.

6 Precipitation and Departure Delay

Figure 6.1 The Mean and Median Lineplot of Departure Delay over the Precipitation

The mean and median plots above shows fluctuations of departure delays as precipitation increases. Since it does not indicate a significant difference between median and mean, due to the existence of great number of outlier, we will do a permutation test on median difference of high and low precipitations.

6.1 High Precipitation vs Low Precipitation

Table 6.2 The Median of Departure Delay with respect to High and Low Precipitation
Median(High Precipitation) Median(Low Precipitation)
9 0

\(H_{0}: Med_{P} - Med_{p} = 0\)
\(H_{a}: Med_{P} - Med_{p} > 0\)

In the conclusion, since p-value is 10^{-4} (less than 0.05), it is statistically significant to say that there is a median difference of departure delays between high and low precipitation.

7 Visibility and Departure Delay

Figure 7.1 The Mean and Median Lineplot of Departure Delay over the Visibility

From the box-plot and mean line-plot of departure delays vs visibility, it seems that mean shows a significant differences in comparison. Besides, it seems that low visibility tends to have a higher departure delays than high visibility. Therefore, we will do a permutation test on mean difference of departure delays with respect to visibility.

7.1 High visibility vs Low visibility

Table 7.2 The Mean of Departure Delay with respect to High and Low Visibility
Mean(High Visibility) Mean(Low Visibility)
11.74591 17.89801

\(H_{0}: \mu_{V} - \mu_{v} = 0\)
\(H_{a}: \mu_{V} - \mu_{v} > 0\)

In the conclusion, since p-value is 10^{-4} (less than 0.05), it is statistically significant to say that there is a mean difference of departure delays between high and low visibility.
